AGI - The wave of bad weather and the collapse of temperatures in Northern Italy is leading to the re-ignition of heating in many cities, from Genoa to Venice. Many mayors signed ordinances to derogate from the end of the thermal season taken between 8 and 15 April, derogations provided for in Article 4 of the Decree of the President of the Republic number 74 of 2013 that regulates the matter. In Genoa, the optional re-ignition of heating systems was established until 30 April for a maximum of 6 hours daily at normal rate (19 degrees +2 of tolerance for homes). In Turin, the municipality recalled the possibility of ignition by derogation of heating systems (maximum 19 degrees in the house) up to a maximum of 7 hours daily, between 5 and 23.
&nbsp;
No order in Milan but Palazzo Marino has remembered that "outside the allowed ignition period and without any further disposition of the authorities" it is possible to turn on the heats if the climatic situation requires it "for a daily duration" not more than seven hours and with maximum temperatures for the houses of 19 degrees plus two of tolerance. In Pordenone the shutdown of the heating systems has been postponed to 28 April inclusive, for a maximum of 6 hours and 30 minutes per day.
&nbsp;
In Venice an order of the mayor Luigi Brugnaro authorizes until 28 April the optional ignition of the thermal plants for a maximum of 14 hours daily. In Verona the extension is until 30 April for no more than seven hours daily (maximum temperature of 19 degrees in the house) and similar measures were adopted by Padua, Vicenza, Treviso and other Venetian cities. Prorogation until 26 April in Bologna, with the invitation to limit the ignition in the coldest hours, up to a maximum of 6 hours daily, and not to exceed the temperature of 19 degrees. In Modena the extension arrives until 28 April, in Ravenna until 30.&nbsp;

