AGI -&nbsp;In Lombardy, more than 4.280 premature parts have been recorded > (within the 37th week) in 2022 and in the world premature birth is the main cause of death for children under five years, with about 900.000 neonatal deaths recorded each year. Although the causes of premature births are not yet clear, it is suspected that the environment may be among the main triggering factors. To respond to this phenomenon, the research project TinyTrend led by Albert Navarro Gallinad, health data scientist of Human Technopole and member of the research group of Luisa Zuccolo, will study which environmental factors contribute to the premature parts in order to inform future prevention policies.
&nbsp;
"TinyTrend" is one of two projects thanks to which Human Technopole> has obtained the prestigious Marie Skodowska-Curie actions postdoctoral fellowship (MSCA) of the European Commission. The other is the project Prune developed by scientist Carlos Jimènez, postdoc of the researcher team Magda Bienko, who will study the spatial arrangement of proteins within the cell core as this helps to optimize the functioning of the cell itself. Each of the two fellowships is over 172,000 euros for a duration of two years.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Thanks to a collaboration already in existence with the Lombardy Region,> Albert Navarro Gallinad will have access to the health data of the births recorded in Lombardy over the past twelve years, estimated in almost one million children. This data will be crossed, through the use of an AI, with other information sets > inert to the regulatory changes of risk reduction policies that have occurred over the years. For example, the project will investigate how the frequency of premature parts changes as a result of the introduction of traffic reduction policies. This will allow you to combine the dots between the role of air pollution and the risk for pregnant women, using policy change as a natural experiment. This innovative approach will allow to identify additional environmental causes > related to premature parts.
&nbsp;
TinyTrend will therefore represent a best practice for other Italian regions, generating knowledge that can also be transferred to the study of other pathologies with a strong environmental component and the causes still uncertain. The project also provides for the development of a website that will include an educational space in which the results of research will be presented, which will be available in Italian, English and Spanish, so as to be able to reach women from different contexts. The site will also join Agenda 2030> for the sustainable development of the United Nations Organization and the Global Health Strategy for Women, Children and Adolescents developed by the World Health Organization (WHO).
<br Carlos Jimènez's "PRUNE" project originates from the fact that the cell nucleus is not homogeneous. Most of its components are not distributed evenly, but take on a peculiar three-dimensional arrangement that helps to physically keep separate processes that would otherwise be incompatible and optimize the distribution of functions. For this reason, researchers believe that proteins, the main performers of biological functions, should have a specific spatial distribution within the cell nucleus and that this significantly affects some vital processes of the cell. To verify this hypothesis, Carlos Jimènez will develop a new method to identify and map the three-dimensional layout of all core proteins in different types of cells, from stems to genetically modified cells, and their functions. In addition to establishing a further levy on the basic knowledge of the cell, in the future this information could provide tools to identify new therapeutic targets for the treatment of certain diseases.
&nbsp;
The Director of Human Technopole Marino Zerial underlines: "These prestigious scholarships obtained by our researchers confirm the need and importance of investing in young people, including and above all in the scientific world, and confirm once again the great commitment of Human Technopole in his mission to improve the health of people and in his formative role for the next generations of scientists. The studies of Albert Navarro Gallinad and Carlos Jimènez will combine big data with artificial intelligence and three-dimensional mapping technologies of the human genome". &nbsp;

